{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is at the module boundary between request builder and API client wiring; a pure unit test of one helper can miss dropped labels during handoff. Real OS/network is not required, and correctness does not depend on model judgment. Rejected higher levels: behavior text is about request payload inclusion, not live provider behavior.","test_description":"Wire classifier module to a stub API client that records outbound payload; call classify with a taxonomy and assert the sent request contains every taxonomy label exactly once.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is local normalization/guard logic: given raw label + taxonomy, output must map out-of-taxonomy values to \"unknown\". The failure can be caught at one function/object boundary without I/O. Rejected higher levels: behavior text focuses on value mapping rule, not transport, OS, or model quality.","test_description":"Call normalization/classification decision function with taxonomy [legal, technical, financial, other] and raw label \"medical\"; assert output is \"unknown\".","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.72,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Behavior explicitly targets determinism of the normalization step itself; this is pure local logic with no required module handoff or I/O. Rejected higher levels: text says \"identical raw API responses\" and tests only normalization determinism, not live API behavior.","test_description":"Invoke normalization repeatedly with the same raw response fixture (including casing/whitespace variants normalized internally) and assert identical final label every run.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly requires repeated live AI API calls and consistency conditional on provider output; mocking replaces model behavior and can hide real drift/non-determinism in returned labels. This is not multi-step agent pipeline, so not Workflow.","test_description":"Run N repeated real provider calls with fixed document/taxonomy, log raw provider label and final module label per call, and assert final label changes only on calls where provider raw label changed.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.22,"Agentic":0.63,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure appears at interaction between token-budget enforcement and dispatch gate (truncate/reject then send or block). In-process wiring with stub client is sufficient; no real OS/network required and no dependence on model output quality. Rejected higher levels: behavior says \"before dispatch\" policy enforcement, not live provider semantics.","test_description":"Configure small token budget, call classify with over-budget document, and assert policy outcome (truncate or reject) plus whether API client was called or blocked according to policy.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Requires real provider-reported usage from an AI API call; stubs cannot catch mismatches caused by real model/provider token accounting behavior. Real network is involved, but the critical dependency is live AI service response fields. Rejected Workflow: only single-call behavior, not chained agentic stages.","test_description":"Send representative document to real provider through module, capture provider usage metadata returned for that call, and assert reported input/output/total tokens are within configured budget threshold.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.34,"Agentic":0.58,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Best caught by wiring retry/backoff logic with API client behavior (rate-limit then success). A deterministic stub can reproduce failure boundary; real OS/network is unnecessary, and correctness does not depend on model output content. Rejected higher levels: behavior text is retry orchestration on rate-limit signal, not live model judgment.","test_description":"Use stub client to return rate-limit error (e.g., 429/Retry-After) then success; assert module delays per policy, retries expected count, and returns successful label instead of propagating initial error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilitie